6.Text: AN035W was drilled by Arrow Energy using the rotary air method during December 2013 and reached
a tota depth of 30.0m on 6 December 2013.
It spudded on 6 December 2013, whereupon a 140mm (5.5") PDC bit was drilled from 0.0m to 30.0m.
A 	uPVC bore of 62mm (OD) was installed in compliance with the Minimum Construction Requirements
for Water Bores in Australia (2012). The bore was constructed to be open to the aquifer through a
40um aperture slotted casing between 20.0m and 29.0m with a sump from 29.0m to 30.0m. A gravel
pack was installed across the screened interval from 19.5m to 30.0m and a bentonite seal was
emplaced between 17.4m and 19.5m. The hole was then cemented from 17.4m to surface. The hole
was completed with a cap and lockable monument.

4.4 REGIONAL GEOLOGY
5 	GEOLOGICAL SUMMARY
5.1 Regional Geologv
5.1.1 Introduction
The Bowen Basin extends from Central to Southern Oueensland, Australia and covers an area of
roughly 60,000 square kilometres. At its southern extent it is overlain by the Mesozoic Surat Basin. It is
contemporaneous with the Gunnedah and Sydney Basins to the South (Esterle et al 2002).
Coal seams in the Bowen Basin exhibit major variations in rank and quality, reflecting both the
depositional and tectonic history of the basin. A broad trend of increasing rank from west to east has
long been recognised, and was used as a guide for coal exploration targets during the late 1950's and
early 1960's (Queensland Department of Natural Resources and Mines 2003). The evolution of the
Bowen Basin can be broken into 4 broad phases; a crustal extension phase, a thermal subsidence
phase, a foreland loading phase and a basin closure phase (Fielding et al 1997).
Crustal Extension
Development of the Bowen Basin initiated during the early-Permian as East-West extension generated a
series of half graben sub-basins. Subsequent partial filling of the sub-basins occurred in the form of
volcanic and sedimentary (lacustrine and fluvial) deposits (i.e. The Reid's Dome Beds - Esterle et al
Thermal Subsidence
Rapid subsidence due to continued thermal sag and continental erosion led to a marine transgression.
From this point onwards deposition within the basin became dominated by coastal and shallow marine
sedimentation (e.g. The Back Creek Group - Table 1-1).
Foreland Loading
Evolution of the Bowen Basin continued into the Late Permian, as further basin opening occurred with
uplift and renewed volcanism in the east of the Basin. During this period the half graben sub-basins
became interconnected with continuing burial by a series of transgressive and regressive events.
The Late Permian deposits of the Blackwater Group are the targets for Arrow Energy. The Blackwater
Group is divided into three terrestrial units, namely the Rangal, Fort Coopers and Moranbah Coal

A period of tectonic compression in the Middle to Late-Triassic terminated any further sedimentation
within the basin resulting in gentle folding and regional faulting (e.g. The Jellinbah Thrust, Figure 1-1).
The area is mantled by an irregular cover of poorly consolidated Tertiary sedimentary strata and basalt
(fresh and weathered). The Tertiary cover unconformably overlies the sediments and main coal-bearing
units of the Late Permian Blackwater Group (Table 1-1).
